        "type": "text",
        "text": "Perfect! Circuit built successfully. Here's your counter setup:\n\n## Wiring Table\n\n| Arduino Pin | Component         | Pin Role |\n|-------------|-------------------|----------|\n| D2          | 7-segment seg-a   | signal (via 220Ω) |\n| D3          | 7-segment seg-b   | signal (via 220Ω) |\n| D4          | 7-segment seg-c   | signal (via 220Ω) |\n| D5          | 7-segment seg-d   | signal (via 220Ω) |\n| D6          | 7-segment seg-e   | signal (via 220Ω) |\n| D7          | 7-segment seg-f   | signal (via 220Ω) |\n| D8          | 7-segment seg-g   | signal (via 220Ω) |\n| GND         | 7-segment common  | ground   |\n| D9          | Button pin A      | signal (pulled HIGH internally) |\n| GND         | Button pin B      | ground   |\n\n## Sketch Behavior\n\nThe sketch initializes the counter at 0 and displays it on the 7-segment. The button uses `INPUT_PULLUP` (active-LOW detection). Each press increments the counter; after 9, it wraps back to 0. The `displayDigit()` function maps each digit (0–9) to its segment pattern.\n\n## Power Budget\n\n- **Per-pin draw**: Each segment pin sources ~2 mA (segment resistor 220Ω ÷ ~1.4V LED drop).\n- **Peak load** (all 7 segments + button): ~14 mA total.\n- **Safety**: Well within Arduino Uno 40 mA per I/O group and 200 mA total budget. ✓\n\nPress the button to increment!"
      }
